'''Collaborative bargaining''' is a style of [[negotiation]] which recognises the interests of the other party and emphasises [[cooperation]] between them.  It was especially promoted, practised and studied in the negotiations between [[school district]]s and [[:category:education trade unions|teaching union]]s in the United States in the 1990s.  It is compared and contrasted with more adversarial models of [[collective bargaining]] in which the parties may regard each other as enemies.<ref>{{citation |pages=41–44 |chapter=Collaborative Bargaining vs. Collective Bargaining |title=An empirical analysis of educator beliefs related to post-industrial labor reforms in the State of Oregon |author=Gregory Paul Sampson-Gruener |year=2009 |isbn=978-1-109-04294-8}}</ref>

