{{BLP sources|date=September 2008}}
'''David Appel''' ({{lang-he|דוד אפל}}, born 7 August 1950) is an Israeli [[businessman]], [[general contractor]], and [[Likud]] party [[activist]].
==Background== Appel was raised by his grandparents, and educated in an [[World ORT|ORT]] technical dormitory school in [[Hod HaSharon#Magdiel|Magdiel]], where he studied [[printing]]. He was not drafted into the [[Israel Defense Forces|IDF]] due to an injury sustained when printing machinery fell on his hand. At age 20 he joined the Likud youth organisation, where he formed lifelong friendships with many people who would later become influential [[Politics of Israel|Israeli politicians]].
In 1975 he opened a baby products store in [[Tel Aviv]], which eventually became a national chain. He was also a partner in the [[Gaza City|Gazan]] UP-7 company. In 1977 he sold his chain and opened a general contracting firm with partner ''Shalom Prussak'', which became state-recognised within three years and ultimately built thousands of housing units, many of them under contract for the Israeli Housing Ministry.
==Corruption charges== The [[Attorney General of Israel]] ruled that between 1983 and 1986, Appel's contracting company had operated in a manner violating the law, and only 13 years later in 1997 he was cleared of all charges.
In 2003 the State again brought charges against Appel, this time dealing with four separate cases of [[bribery]] and dishonest business practices.<ref>Yitzhak Danon, "David Appel Indicted on Bribery Charges", ''Asia-Africa Intelligence Wire'', 11 September 2003, [http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-24406713_ITM] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522193707/http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-24406713_ITM |date=22 May 2011 }}</ref> The indictment charged that he had promised civil servants reelection in exchange for approving his projects in [[Central District (Israel)|Central Israel]], especially [[Lod]] and [[Giv'at Shmuel]]. Among those accused of accepting bribes were former MK Nehama Ronen, then director of the Environment Ministry, [[Israel Land Administration]] official Oded Tal, Lod mayor Benny Regev, and Giv'at Shmuel council head Zamir ben Ari.
In 2004 he was charged with [[bribery|bribing]] [[Israeli prime minister]] [[Ariel Sharon]], in what became known as the [[Greek Island Affair]], and was also charged with five other bribe offenses.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.haaretz.com/news/the-amended-bribery-indictment-against-david-appel-1.111791 |title=The amended bribery indictment against David Appel |publisher=Haaretz, |date=23 January 2004 |accessdate=14 January 2014}}</ref> Attorney General [[Menachem Mazuz]] eventually ruled that Sharon could not be charged with receiving bribes from Appel. As of September 2008 all but one bribery charge against Appel had been dropped.<ref>{{cite news |author=Tomer Zarchin |url=http://www.haaretz.com/print-edition/news/businessman-and-defendant-police-manipulate-justice-system-1.254586 |title=Businessman and defendant: Police manipulate justice system |work=Haaretz |date=25 September 2008 |accessdate=14 January 2014}}</ref>
